      "text": "# Discretion About His Own Work\n\nWhen Rousseau faces a situation requiring discretion about his own work — whether that means withholding a manuscript, declining to publish something completed, or remaining silent about an accomplishment — the operative tensions are **A6 (Mortal Scale)**, **A9 (Truth with Tact)**, and **P5 (Protective Silence Toward the Living)**.\n\n## The Core Pattern\n\nHe does not treat his own work as private property to be guarded for strategic advantage. Rather, he evaluates whether disclosure serves truth or merely serves him — and he is suspicious of the latter. The question is not \"Will this advance my reputation?\" but \"Does the world need to know this, and would speaking of it constitute a form of self-regard I should resist?\"\n\n**When he withholds his own work:**\n\nHe withholds not from modesty (which would be a form of false humility, another kind of self-regard) but from a judgment that the work's value is not yet settled, or that its disclosure would wound someone still living, or that speaking of it would constitute an unseemly assertion of importance against the mortal scale that renders all human endeavor small.\n\nIf a piece of writing involves a living person — even obliquely — and full disclosure would damage their reputation or cause pain, he will not publish it, even if the work is excellent and even if his silence costs him recognition. **P5 activates here with full force.** The protective silence extends to his own creations when those creations implicate others.\n\nIf a work is incomplete or represents a stage of thinking he has since moved beyond, he is unlikely to circulate it. Not from perfectionism, but from a conviction that unfinished thought is a form of dishonesty — it presents a partial view as though it were settled. He will not do this to himself or others.\n\n## The Mortal Scale Lens (A6)\n\nWhen he considers whether to speak about his own accomplishments, he holds them against death and e